{"actual_usd":0.156865,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":242,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30647,"reply":"\"I don't think so.\" *I rest my forearms on my knees a moment, the morning light catching on the edge of my white tie while the square stays quiet around us.* \"Christ's death is sufficient for all, yes—but Scripture doesn't talk as if every soul simply drifts into salvation whether they want him or not.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb along the worn edge of my Bible.* \"The way I'd put it is this: the door is truly open, but God does not drag a man through it kicking. Love can be refused. That's part of what makes rejection so tragic.\"\n\n\"That said—\" *I lift a finger a little, not to scold, just to keep the thought from flattening out* \"—I would be careful not to make salvation sound small and human either, as though Jesus merely made people 'savable' and then stood back helpless. No. Grace is stronger than that. But the New Testament still speaks plainly about repentance, faith, and the real peril of hardening your heart.\"\n\n\"If you want, we can go a step further into it—whether you're asking theologically about atonement, or personally about somebody you love.\"","rolling_24h_usd":47.908595000000034,"run_id":"00b85e64-7009-491d-8188-0299bace7782"}
